Answer: Binary search is a divide and conquer technique. It divides the range into two parts and then compares the target value with each part.

For example, if you have a range from 1 to 100 and you are searching for 50, then the range is divided into two equal parts, 1 to 50 and 50 to 100. Then 50 is compared with each part. If 50 is smaller than the first part, the search is done in the first part, otherwise, it is done in the second part.

If the search is done in the first part, it is divided again into two parts. This continues until the target value is found or it is out of the range.

```
public static int binarySearch(int[] arr, int target) {
    int low = 0;
    int high = arr.length - 1;
    int mid;

    while (low <= high) {
        mid = (low + high) / 2;
        if (arr[mid] == target) {
            return mid;
        }

        if (target < arr[mid]) {
            low = mid + 1;
        } else {
            high = mid - 1;
        }
    }

    return -1;
}

```

